<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20


<h1 class=3D"center">Quadratic Equations</h1>=20


<p>An example of a <b>Quadratic Equation</b>:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/q=
uadratic-equation-reason.svg" alt=3D"A Quadratic Equation 5x^2 - 3x + 3 =3D=
 0" height=3D"63" width=3D"285"></p>=20
<p>The function can make nice curves like this one:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/geometry/parabola=
.html"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/quadratic-socc=
er.gif" alt=3D"quadratic soccer kick" height=3D"150" width=3D"266"></a></p>=
=20


<h2>Name</h2>=20

<div class=3D"words">=20
<p>The name <b>Quadratic</b> comes from "quad" meaning square, because the =
variable gets <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/square-root.html">squar=
ed</a> (like <b>x<sup>2</sup></b>).</p>=20
<p>It is also called an "Equation of <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/=
algebra/degree-expression.html">Degree</a> 2" (because of the "2" on the <b=
>x</b>)</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Standard Form</h2>=20

<p>The <b>Standard Form</b> of a Quadratic Equation looks like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/q=
uadratic-equation.svg" alt=3D"Quadratic Equation: ax^2 + bx + c =3D 0" heig=
ht=3D"33" width=3D"301"><br></p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li><b>a</b>, <b>b</b> and <b>c</b> are known values. <b>a</b> can't be 0<=
/li>=20

	<li><b>x</b> is the <b><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/defin=
itions.html">variable</a></b> or unknown (we don't know it yet)</li>=20
</ul>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>Here are some  examples:</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr>
			<td class=3D"larger" style=3D"white-space: nowrap; text-align: right;"><=
b>2x<sup>2</sup> + 5x + 3 =3D 0</b></td>
			<td style=3D"width:20px;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td>In this one <b>a=3D2</b>, <b>b=3D5</b> and <b>c=3D3</b></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td style=3D"text-align: right;">&nbsp;</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger" style=3D"text-align: right;"><b>x<sup>2</sup> =E2=
=88=92 3x =3D 0</b></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td> This one is a little more tricky:=20
<ul>=20
	<li>Where is <b>a</b>? Well <b>a=3D1</b>, as we don't usually write "1x<su=
p>2</sup>"</li>=20
	<li><b>b =3D =E2=88=923</b></li>=20
	<li>And where is <b>c</b>? Well <b>c=3D0</b>, so is not shown.</li>=20
</ul></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class=3D"larger" style=3D"text-align: right;"><b>5x =E2=88=92 3 =3D =
0</b></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td>
			<td><b>Oops!</b> This one is <b>not</b> a quadratic equation: it is miss=
ing <b>x<sup>2</sup></b><br>
(in other words <b>a=3D0</b>, which means it can't be quadratic)</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20



<div class=3D"fun">
	<p class=3D"floatRt"><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/quadrat=
ic-equation-graph.html"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/imag=
es/quadratic-graph.svg" alt=3D"Quadratic Graph" height=3D"140" width=3D"175=
"></a></p>=20
	<h3>Have a Play With It</h3>=20
=09
	<p>Play with the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/quadratic-e=
quation-graph.html">Quadratic Equation Explorer</a> so you can see:</p>=20
	<ul class=3D"dart">
		<li>the function's graph, and</li>
		<li>the solutions (called "roots").</li>
	</ul>
</div>


<h2>Hidden Quadratic Equations!</h2>=20

<p>As we saw before, the <b>Standard Form</b> of a Quadratic Equation is</p=
>=20
<div class=3D"def center larger">=20
ax<sup>2</sup> + bx + c =3D 0=20
</div>=20

<p>But sometimes a quadratic equation does not look like that!</p>=20
<p>For example:</p>=20
<div class=3D"simple">

	<table style=3D"border: 0; margin:auto;">
		<tbody><tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<th scope=3D"col">In disguise</th>
			<th scope=3D"col" class=3D"large"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com=
/images/style/right-arrow.gif" alt=3D"right arrow" height=3D"46" width=3D"4=
6"></th>
			<th scope=3D"col">In Standard Form</th>
			<th scope=3D"col">a, b and c</th>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td><b>x<sup>2</sup> =3D 3x =E2=88=92 1</b></td>
			<td>Move all terms to left hand side</td>
			<td><b>x<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 3x + 1 =3D 0</b></td>
			<td>a=3D1, b=3D=E2=88=923, c=3D1</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td><b>2(w<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 2w) =3D 5</b></td>
			<td><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/expanding.html">Expand=
</a> (undo the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/brackets.html"=
>brackets</a>),<br>
and move 5 to left</td>
			<td><b>2w<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 4w =E2=88=92 5 =3D 0</b></td>
			<td>a=3D2, b=3D=E2=88=924, c=3D=E2=88=925</td>
		</tr>
		<tr style=3D"text-align:center;">
			<td><b>z(z=E2=88=921) =3D 3</b></td>
			<td>Expand, and move 3 to left</td>
			<td><b>z<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 z =E2=88=92 3 =3D 0</b></td>
			<td>a=3D1, b=3D=E2=88=921, c=3D=E2=88=923</td>
		</tr>
	</tbody></table>=20
</div>=20



<h2>How To Solve Them?</h2>=20

<div class=3D"words">=20
<p>The "<b>solutions</b>" to the Quadratic Equation are where it is <b>equa=
l to zero</b>.</p>=20
<p>They are also called "<b>roots</b>", or sometimes "<b>zeros</b>"</p>=20
</div>
<p style=3D"float:left; margin: 0 10px 5px 0;"><img src=3D"https://www.math=
sisfun.com/algebra/images/quadratic-graph.svg" alt=3D"Quadratic Graph" heig=
ht=3D"140" width=3D"175"></p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>There are usually 2 solutions (as shown in this graph).</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>And there are a few different ways to find the solutions:</p>=20
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>
<div class=3D"dotpoint"> We can <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algeb=
ra/factoring-quadratics.html">Factor the Quadratic</a> (find what to multip=
ly to make the Quadratic Equation)=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"dotpoint"> Or we can <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/al=
gebra/completing-square.html">Complete the Square</a>
</div>=20

<div class=3D"dotpoint"> Or we can use the special <b>Quadratic Formula</b>=
:=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/q=
uadratic-formula.svg" alt=3D"Quadratic Formula: x =3D [ -b (+-) sqrt(b^2 - =
4ac) ] / 2a" height=3D"79" width=3D"286"></p>=20
<p class=3D"center">Just plug in the values of a, b and c, and do the calcu=
lations.</p>=20
<p>We will look at this method in more detail now.</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>About the Quadratic Formula</h2>=20

<h3>Plus/Minus</h3>=20

<p>First of all what is that plus/minus thing that looks like <span class=
=3D"largest">=C2=B1 </span>?</p>=20
<p class=3D"so">The <span class=3D"large">=C2=B1</span> means there are TWO=
 answers:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>=E2=88=92b <spa=
n class=3D"hilite">+</span> =E2=88=9A(b<sup>2 </sup>=E2=88=92 4ac)</em> <st=
rong>2a</strong> </span></p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>=E2=88=92b <spa=
n class=3D"hilite">=E2=88=92</span> =E2=88=9A(b<sup>2 </sup>=E2=88=92 4ac)<=
/em> <strong>2a</strong></span></p>=20
<p>Here is an example with two answers:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/q=
uadratic-graph.svg" alt=3D"Quadratic Graph" height=3D"140" width=3D"175"></=
p>=20
<p>But it does not always work out like that!</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>Imagine if the curve "just touches" the x-axis.</li>=20
	<li>Or imagine  the curve is so <b>high</b> it doesn't even cross the x-ax=
is!</li>
</ul>=20
<p>This is where  the "Discriminant" helps us ...</p>=20

<h3>Discriminant</h3>=20

<p class=3D"indent50px">Do you see <b>b<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 4ac</b> in th=
e formula above? It is called the <b>Discriminant</b>, because it can "disc=
riminate" between the possible types of answer:</p>=20
<div class=3D"bigul">=20
<ul>=20
	<li class=3D"indent50px">when <b>b<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 4ac</b> is positi=
ve, we get two <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/real-numbers.h=
tml">Real</a> solutions</li>=20
	<li class=3D"indent50px">when it is zero we get just ONE real solution (bo=
th answers are the same)</li>=20
	<li class=3D"indent50px">when it is negative we get a pair of  <a href=3D"=
https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/complex-numbers.html">Complex</a> soluti=
ons</li>=20
</ul>=20
</div>=20

<p class=3D"indent50px"><i>Complex solutions?</i> Let's talk about them aft=
er we see how to use the formula.</p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20

<h3>Using the Quadratic Formula</h3>=20

<p>Just put the values of a, b and c into the Quadratic Formula, and do the=
 calculations.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Solve 5x<sup>2</sup> + 6x + 1 =3D 0</h3>=20

	<div class=3D"tbl">=20
	<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">Coefficients are:</span><span clas=
s=3D"right">a =3D 5, b =3D 6, c =3D 1</span></div>
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">Quadratic Formula:</span><span clas=
s=3D"right"><span class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>=E2=88=
=92b =C2=B1 =E2=88=9A(b<sup>2 </sup>=E2=88=92 4ac)</em> <strong>2a</strong>=
 </span></span> </span></div>
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">Put in a, b and c:</span><span clas=
s=3D"right"><span class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>=E2=88=
=926 =C2=B1 =E2=88=9A(6<sup>2 </sup>=E2=88=92 4=C3=975=C3=971)</em> <strong=
>2=C3=975</strong> </span></span> </span></div>
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">Solve:</span><span class=3D"right">=
<span class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>=E2=88=926 =C2=B1 =
=E2=88=9A(36=E2=88=92 20)</em> <strong>10</strong> </span></span> </span></=
div>
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"right">=
<span class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>=E2=88=926 =C2=B1 =
=E2=88=9A(16)</em> <strong>10</strong> </span></span> </span></div>
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"right">=
<span class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>=E2=88=926 =C2=B1 4=
</em> <strong>10</strong> </span></span> </span></div>
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"right">=
x =3D =E2=88=920,2 <b>or</b> =E2=88=921</span></div>
</div>=20

<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
graph-5x2p6xp1.svg" alt=3D"5x^2+6x+1" height=3D"140" width=3D"175"><br>And =
we see them on this graph.</p>=20
<p class=3D"larger center"><b>Answer:</b> x =3D =E2=88=920,2 <b>or</b> x =
=3D =E2=88=921</p>=20

<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>
<p>Let's check the answers:</p>=20
<div class=3D"two">
	<div class=3D"lt">Check <b>=E2=88=920,2</b>:</div>
	<div class=3D"rt">5=C3=97(<b>=E2=88=920,2</b>)<sup>2</sup> + 6=C3=97(<b>=
=E2=88=920,2</b>) + 1<br>
=3D 5=C3=97(0,04) + 6=C3=97(=E2=88=920,2) + 1<br>
=3D 0,2 =E2=88=92 1,2 + 1<br>
<b>=3D 0</b></div>
	<div class=3D"lt">Check <b>=E2=88=921</b>:</div>
	<div class=3D"rt">5=C3=97(<b>=E2=88=921</b>)<sup>2</sup> + 6=C3=97(<b>=E2=
=88=921</b>) + 1<br>
=3D 5=C3=97(1) + 6=C3=97(=E2=88=921) + 1<br>
=3D 5 =E2=88=92 6 + 1<br>
<b>=3D 0</b></div>
</div>


	=20
</div>=20

<p>&nbsp;</p>=20

<h3>Remembering The Formula</h3>=20

<p>A kind reader suggested singing it to "Pop Goes the Weasel":</p>=20
<div class=3D"center80 center">

	<div class=3D"box"><span class=3D"times">=E2=99=AB</span> All around the m=
ulberry bush<br>The monkey chased the weasel<br>The monkey thought 'twas al=
l in fun<br>Pop! goes the weasel <span class=3D"times">=E2=99=AB</span></di=
v>
	<div class=3D"box"><span class=3D"times">=E2=99=AB</span> x is equal to mi=
nus b<br>plus or minus the square root<br>of b-squared minus  four a c<br>A=
LL over two a <span class=3D"times">=E2=99=AB</span></div>

	=20
</div>=20

<p>Try singing it a few times and it will get stuck in your head!</p>=20
<p>Or you can remember this story:</p>=20
<div class=3D"center80">=20
<p class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>=E2=88=92b =C2=B1 =E2=
=88=9A(b<sup>2 </sup>=E2=88=92 4ac)</em> <strong>2a</strong> </span></p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><i>"A negative boy was thinking yes or no about going t=
o a party,<br>
at the party he talked to a square boy but not to the  4 awesome chicks.<br=
>
It was all over at 2 am.</i>"</p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Complex Solutions?</h2>=20

<p>When the Discriminant (the value <b>b<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 4ac</b>) is =
negative we get a pair of <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/com=
plex-numbers.html">Complex</a> solutions ... what does that mean?</p>=20
<p>It means our answer will include <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/n=
umbers/imaginary-numbers.html">Imaginary Numbers</a>. Wow!</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Solve 5x<sup>2</sup> + 2x + 1 =3D 0</h3>=20

	<div class=3D"tbl">=20
	<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left"><b>Coefficients</b> are<b>:</b></s=
pan><span class=3D"right">a=3D5, b=3D2, c=3D1</span></div>
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">Note that the <b>Discriminant</b> i=
s negative:</span><span class=3D"right">b<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 4ac =3D 2<s=
up>2</sup> =E2=88=92 4=C3=975=C3=971<br>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; =3D <b>=E2=88=9216</b></sp=
an></div>
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">Use the <b>Quadratic Formula:</b></=
span><span class=3D"right"><span class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intb=
l"> <em>=E2=88=922 =C2=B1 =E2=88=9A(=E2=88=9216)</em> <strong>10</strong> <=
/span></span> </span></div>
<div class=3D"center"><em>=E2=88=9A(=E2=88=9216)</em> =3D 4<b>i</b><br>
(where <b>i</b> is the imaginary number =E2=88=9A=E2=88=921)</div>=20
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">So:</span><span class=3D"right"><sp=
an class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>=E2=88=922 =C2=B1 4<b>=
i</b></em> <strong>10</strong> </span></span> </span></div>
</div>

<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
graph-5x2p2xp1.gif" alt=3D"5x^2+6x+1" height=3D"181" width=3D"178"></p>=20
<p class=3D"larger center"><b>Answer:</b> x =3D =E2=88=920,2 =C2=B1 0,4<b>i=
</b></p>=20
<p>&nbsp;</p>=20
<p>The graph does not cross the x-axis. That is why we ended up with comple=
x numbers.</p>=20
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>
</div>=20

<p>In a way it is easier: we don't need more calculation, we leave it as <s=
pan class=3D"larger">=E2=88=920,2 =C2=B1 0,4<b>i</b></span>.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: Solve x<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 4x + 6,25 =3D 0</h3>=20

	<div class=3D"tbl">=20
	<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left"><b>Coefficients</b> are<b>:</b></s=
pan><span class=3D"right">a=3D1, b=3D=E2=88=924, c=3D6,25</span></div>
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">Note that the <b>Discriminant</b> i=
s negative:</span><span class=3D"right">b<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 4ac =3D (=
=E2=88=924)<sup>2</sup> =E2=88=92 4=C3=971=C3=976,25<br>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; =3D <b>=E2=88=929</b></spa=
n></div>
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">Use the <b>Quadratic Formula:</b></=
span><span class=3D"right"><span class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intb=
l"> <em>=E2=88=92(=E2=88=924) =C2=B1 =E2=88=9A(=E2=88=929)</em> <strong>2</=
strong> </span></span> </span></div>
<div class=3D"center"><em>=E2=88=9A(=E2=88=929)</em> =3D 3<b>i</b><br>
(where <b>i</b> is the imaginary number =E2=88=9A=E2=88=921)</div>=20
<div class=3D"row"><span class=3D"left">So:</span><span class=3D"right"><sp=
an class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl"> <em>4 =C2=B1 3<b>i</b></em=
> <strong>2</strong> </span></span> </span></div>
</div>=20

<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
quadratic-graph-complex-a.svg" alt=3D"Quadratic Graph with Cmplex Roots" he=
ight=3D"140" width=3D"175"></p>=20
<p class=3D"larger center"><b>Answer:</b> x =3D 2 =C2=B1 1,5<b>i</b></p>=20
<p>The graph does not cross the x-axis. That is why we ended up with comple=
x numbers.</p>=20
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>
<p class=3D"floatLt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algebra/images/=
quadratic-graph-complex.svg" alt=3D"Quadratic Graph with Cmplex Roots" heig=
ht=3D"140" width=3D"175"></p>=20
<p>BUT an <b>upside-down mirror image</b> of our equation does cross the x-=
axis at <span class=3D"larger center">2 =C2=B1 1,5</span> (note: missing th=
e <b>i</b>).</p>=20
<p>Just an interesting fact for you!</p>=20
<div style=3D"clear:both"></div>
</div>=20

<p>&nbsp;</p>=20


<h2>Summary</h2>=20

<ul class=3D"larger">=20
	<li>Quadratic Equation in Standard Form: ax<sup>2</sup> + bx + c =3D 0</li=
>=20
	<li>Quadratic Equations can be <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/algeb=
ra/factoring-quadratics.html">factored</a></li>=20
	<li>Quadratic Formula: <span class=3D"center">x =3D <span class=3D"intbl">=
 <em>=E2=88=92b =C2=B1 =E2=88=9A(b<sup>2 </sup>=E2=88=92 4ac)</em> <strong>=
2a</strong> </span></span></li>=20
	<li>When the Discriminant (<b>b<sup>2</sup>=E2=88=924ac</b>) is:=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>positive, there are 2 real solutions</li>=20
		<li>zero, there is one real solution</li>=20
		<li>negative, there are 2 complex solutions</li>=20
	</ul>
	</li>=20
</ul>
